			</td><td width="2%">&nbsp;</td><td width="44%"> Abstract
			<div style="text-align:justify;">
				<P>
					<B>Introduction</B>: The orchid family, about 20,000 species, is one of the largest botanical families. In Brazil it is estimated that the number could reach 2,300 species. Parana, are registered 123 genera and 594 native species.					<B>Objectives</B>: The objectives were to identify the Orchidaceae, provide information about the time of flowering, geographic distribution, habitat, endemism and if there is risk of extinction for the species.					<B>Methods</B>: This work was carried out in Conservation Unit of Palmito State Forest (EFF) area located in the Paraná coastal plain in the municipality of Paranaguá. The phytogeographic area of the region is characterized by the presence of dense rain forest of Lowlands, Pioneer Training with Influence tidal river, and Pioneer Training with Influence Navy. The primary forest has been removed in the past to make way for cassava and pineapple crops, and is currently in the middle stage of advanced regeneration.
Fortnightly collections were made from the beginning of January with planning to end in December. The specimens were found herborized and will be stored as the traditional methods for the group.					<B>Results</B>: For the EFF were found 50 species distributed in 30 Genres, Octomeria R.Br. Epidendrum L. and the most abundant genera, with 5 representatives each. Have found no endemic copy for the state, andreana Octomeria Campacci [e] Baptista is a possible reoccurrence, and Octomeria alexandri Schltr. It is a species that is on the endangered list for the country in the category of "endangered (EN)." By comparing the data found in working with others conducted in conservation areas for the Paraná coastal plain, we found that aa wealth of the group in FEP is the highest, and the similiaridade between areas is low. This is due to human action arising from the population in other areas compared expanção be more intense in recent decades.					<B>Conclusion</B>: We conclude that the EFF is a protected area important for the preservation of Orchidaceae mainly by the presence of a listed as threatened endangered species.				</P>
